This paper is likely to belong to the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category as it deals with optimizing news headlines to increase readership and user engagement. It also involves testing different variations of headlines to find the best-performing one, which is a common problem in information retrieval. 

The paper also involves machine learning techniques such as multi-armed bandit and Thompson Sampling, which are commonly used in the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. 

The paper also deals with user engagement and social shares, which are related to the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category. 

The paper involves simulations and empirical data analysis, which are related to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category. 

Finally, the paper involves natural language processing techniques to optimize headlines, which is related to the Computation and Language (cs.CL) sub-category.
